net.akami.mask.expression

Interface Variable

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    IntricateVariable, SingleCharVariable

    public interface Variable
    An immutable mathematical unknown. Two implementation of this interface exist, being SingleCharVariable and IntricateVariable.
    A list of variables goes along with a coefficient, both forming a monomial. Complex variables are recursive, by handling a list of monomials, which also contain variables. The end of the recursivity chain is made by single char variables, which are simple unknown such as "x" or "y", or by NumberElements, a kind of monomial that does not contain any unknown part.
    Examples :
  • z is a SingleCharVariable, with no overlay except the implicit ^1 exponent. Its list of monomials has a size of 1, the only monomial being 1x
  • sin(a+b) is an IntricateVariable, with one overlay being sin, and two elements (monomials) being a and b. These elements are both monomials with a SingleCharVariable as their unique variable.
Author:
Antoine Tran

    • Method Detail

      • getExpression

        java.lang.String getExpression()
        For display only. Note that all methods returning strings should not be used for algebraic treatment at all.
        They are used recursively by the getExpression() method from the Expression class, to print the final result of the calculation
        Returns:
        the literal form of the variable, x or sin(y^2) for instance.

      • getAbsoluteOverlays

        java.util.List<ExpressionOverlay> getAbsoluteOverlays()
        Used to retrieve all the overlays of the variable, including the implicit ^1 exponent.
        Returns:
        the list of all overlays encapsulating the current variable.

      • getOverlay

        ExpressionOverlay getOverlay(int i)
        Used to retrieve the overlay at the given index.
        At least in the implementations provided by the library, negative indexes are supported. Therefore, 0 will give the first element, -1 the last one, -2 the penultimate one, etc.
        Note that the only index supported for SingleCharVariables is -1, being the implicit ^1 exponent.
        Parameters:
        i - the index of the list of overlays
        Returns:
        the overlay present at the given index

      • getOverlaysSection

        java.util.List<ExpressionOverlay> getOverlaysSection(int start,
                                                     int end)
        Used to retrieve a section of the list of overlays, from a given start (included) to a given end (included). Calling this method from a SingleCharVariable will always return an empty list. If you want to retrieve all overlays from a SingleCharVariable including the explicit one, use getAbsoluteOverlays() instead.
        Parameters:
        start - the start of the section wanted
        end - the end of the section wanted
        Returns:
        a list of overlays containing exclusively the overlays with an index included in [start;end]

      • getOverlaysSize

        int getOverlaysSize()
        Returns:
        how many overlays encapsulate the variable

      • getElementsSize

        int getElementsSize()
        Returns:
        how many elements are encapsulated in the variable (always 1 for SingleCharVariables).

      • getElements

        java.util.List<Monomial> getElements()
        Note : all getters return immutable elements.
        Returns:
        the list of elements encapsulated in the variable

      • getNumerator

        java.util.List<Monomial> getNumerator()
        Used to retrieve the numerator of the variable. If the last overlay is not a fraction, then getElements() will be returned. If it is, uncover(-1) will be returned.
        Returns:
        the numerator of the variable

      • getDenominator

        java.util.List<Monomial> getDenominator()
        Used to retrieve the denominator of the variable. If the last overlay is not a fraction, the implicit 1 divider will be returned. If it is, the elements forming the last overlay will be returned.
        Returns:
        the denominator of the variable

      • uncover

        java.util.List<Monomial> uncover(int amount)
        Used to retrieve a list of monomials corresponding to the variable without a given amount of overlays. If the amount given is exactly the amount of overlays, getElements() will be returned. If the amount given is lower than the amount of overlays, a single monomial with a 1 coefficient and the variable without the last overlay will be returned. If the amount of given is greater than the amount of overlays, throws an error.
        Parameters:
        amount - the amount of overlays to fake remove in order to get the list of monomials.
        Returns:
        a list of monomials corresponding to the actual variable without amount overlays

      • getFinalExponent

        java.util.Optional<java.lang.Float> getFinalExponent()
        Used to retrieve the global exponent of the variable. If the last overlay is an exponent, and if the last overlay is a number, then returns Optional.of(number). Otherwise, returns an empty optional
        Returns:
        the global exponent of the variable

      • isFraction

        boolean isFraction()
        Returns:
        whether the last overlay of the variable is a fraction or not

      • getVar

        char getVar()
        Returns:
        the literal char of the variable. Complex variables use recursivity through their elements to determine the char
